  52class Sequence(Generic[T], Iterable[T]):
  53    """
  54    Given an [iterator] function constructs a [Sequence] that returns values through the [Iterator]
  55    provided by that function.
  56
  57    The values are evaluated lazily, and the sequence is potentially infinite.
  58    """
  59
  60    __transform__: Transform[Any, T]
  61
  62    def __init__(self, iterable: Union[Iterable[T], Transform[Any, T]]) -> None:
  63        super().__init__()
  64
  65        self.__transform__ = new_transform(iterable)
  66
  67    @cached_property
  68    def transforms(self):
  69        return [*self.__transform__.transforms()]
  70
  71    @property
  72    def data(self) -> List[T]:
  73        if self.__transform__.cache is None:
  74            from .error import LazyEvaluationException
  75
  76            raise LazyEvaluationException("The sequence has not been evaluated yet.")
  77        return self.__transform__.cache
  78
  79    def dedup(self) -> Sequence[T]:
  80        """
  81        Removes consecutive repeated elements in the sequence.
  82
  83        If the sequence is sorted, this removes all duplicates.
  84
  85        Example 1:
  86        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
  87        >>> it(lst).dedup().to_list()
  88        ['a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
  89
  90        Example 1:
  91        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
  92        >>> it(lst).sorted().dedup().to_list()
  93        ['a1', 'a2', 'b2']
  94        """
  95        return self.dedup_by(lambda x: x)
  96
  97    @overload
  98    def dedup_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T], Any]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
  99    @overload
 100    def dedup_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T, int], Any]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 101    @overload
 102    def dedup_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Any]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 103    def dedup_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., Any]) -> Sequence[T]:
 104        """
 105        Removes all but the first of consecutive elements in the sequence that resolve to the same key.
 106        """
 107        return self.dedup_into_group_by(key_selector).map(lambda x: x[0])

 109    @overload
 110    def dedup_with_count_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T], Any]) -> Sequence[Tuple[T, int]]: ...

 115    @overload
 116    def dedup_with_count_by(
 117        self, key_selector: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Any]
 118    ) -> Sequence[Tuple[T, int]]: ...
 119    def dedup_with_count_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., Any]) -> Sequence[Tuple[T, int]]:
 120        """
 121        Removes all but the first of consecutive elements and its count that resolve to the same key.
 122
 123        Example 1:
 124        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
 125        >>> it(lst).dedup_with_count_by(lambda x: x).to_list()
 126        [('a1', 2), ('b2', 1), ('a2', 1), ('a1', 1)]
 127
 128        Example 1:
 129        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
 130        >>> it(lst).sorted().dedup_with_count_by(lambda x: x).to_list()
 131        [('a1', 3), ('a2', 1), ('b2', 1)]
 132        """
 133        return self.dedup_into_group_by(key_selector).map(lambda x: (x[0], len(x)))
 134

 137    @overload
 138    def dedup_into_group_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T, int], Any]) -> Sequence[List[T]]: ...

 140    def dedup_into_group_by(

 143    def dedup_into_group_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., Any]) -> Sequence[List[T]]:
 144        from .dedup import DedupTransform
 145
 146        return it(DedupTransform(self, key_selector))

 148    @overload
 149    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 150    @overload

 152    @overload
 153    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 154    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
 155        """
 156        Returns a Sequence containing only elements matching the given [predicate].
 157
 158        Example 1:
 159        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
 160        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
 161        ['a1', 'a2']
 162
 163        Example 2:
 164        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
 165        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') or i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
 166        ['a1', 'b2', 'a2']
 167        """
 168        from .filtering import FilteringTransform
 169
 170        return it(FilteringTransform(self, self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)))
 171
 172    def filter_is_instance(self, typ: Type[U]) -> Sequence[U]:
 173        """
 174        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are instances of specified type parameter typ.
 175
 176        Example 1:
 177        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 1, 'b2', 3]
 178        >>> it(lst).filter_is_instance(int).to_list()
 179        [1, 3]
 180
 181        """
 182        return self.filter(lambda x: isinstance(x, typ))  # type: ignore

 184    @overload
 185    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 186    @overload
 187    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 188    @overload
 189    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 190    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
 191        """
 192        Returns a Sequence containing all elements not matching the given [predicate].
 193
 194        Example 1:
 195        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
 196        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
 197        ['b1', 'b2']
 198
 199        Example 2:
 200        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 201        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') and i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
 202        ['a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 203        """
 204        predicate = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)
 205        return self.filter(lambda x: not predicate(x))

 207    @overload
 208    def filter_not_none(self: Sequence[Optional[U]]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 209    @overload
 210    def filter_not_none(self: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 211    def filter_not_none(self: Sequence[Optional[U]]) -> Sequence[U]:
 212        """
 213        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are not `None`.
 214
 215        Example 1:
 216        >>> lst = [ 'a', None, 'b']
 217        >>> it(lst).filter_not_none().to_list()
 218        ['a', 'b']
 219        """
 220        return self.filter(lambda x: x is not None)  # type: ignore

 222    @overload
 223    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T], U]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 224    @overload
 225    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], U]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 226    @overload
 227    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], U]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 228    def map(self, transform: Callable[..., U]) -> Sequence[U]:
 229        """
 230        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 231        to each element in the original Sequence.
 232
 233        Example 1:
 234        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 235        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 236        [12, 13]
 237
 238        Example 2:
 239        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 240        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x, i: x['name'] + str(i)).to_list()
 241        ['A0', 'B1']
 242
 243        Example 3:
 244        >>> lst = ['hi', 'abc']
 245        >>> it(lst).map(len).to_list()
 246        [2, 3]
 247        """
 248        from .mapping import MappingTransform
 249
 250        return it(MappingTransform(self, self.__callback_overload_warpper__(transform)))
 251
 252    @overload
 253    async def map_async(self, transform: Callable[[T], Awaitable[U]]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 254    @overload
 255    async def map_async(
 256        self,
 257        transform: Callable[[T, int], Awaitable[U]],
 258        return_exceptions: Literal[True],

 260    @overload
 261    async def map_async(
 262        self,
 263        transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Awaitable[U]],
 264        return_exceptions: Literal[False] = False,
 265    ) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 266    async def map_async(
 267        self, transform: Callable[..., Awaitable[U]], return_exceptions: bool = False
 268    ):
 269        """
 270        Similar to `.map()` but you can input a async transform then await it.
 271        """
 272        from asyncio import gather
 273
 274        if return_exceptions:
 275            return it(await gather(*self.map(transform), return_exceptions=True))
 276        return it(await gather(*self.map(transform)))
 277
 278    @overload
 279    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[[T], Optional[U]]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 280    @overload
 281    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], Optional[U]]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 282    @overload

 285    ) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 286    def map_not_none(self, transform: Callable[..., Optional[U]]) -> Sequence[U]:
 287        """
 288        Returns a Sequence containing only the non-none results of applying the given [transform] function
 289        to each element in the original collection.
 290
 291        Example 1:
 292        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 293        >>> it(lst).map_not_none(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 294        [12]
 295        """
 296        return self.map(transform).filter_not_none()  # type: ignore

 314    @overload
 315    def parallel_map(
 316        self,
 317        transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], U],
 318        max_workers: Optional[int] = None,
 319        chunksize: int = 1,
 320        executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor = "Thread",
 321    ) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 322    def parallel_map(
 323        self,
 324        transform: Callable[..., U],
 325        max_workers: Optional[int] = None,
 326        chunksize: int = 1,
 327        executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor = "Thread",
 328    ) -> Sequence[U]:
 329        """
 330        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 331        to each element in the original Sequence.
 332
 333        Example 1:
 334        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 335        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 336        [12, 13]
 337
 338        Example 2:
 339        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 340        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age'], max_workers=2).to_list()
 341        [12, 13]
 342
 343        Example 3:
 344        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 345        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x, i: x['age'] + i, max_workers=2).to_list()
 346        [12, 14]
 347        """
 348        from .parallel_mapping import ParallelMappingTransform
 349
 350        return it(
 351            ParallelMappingTransform(
 352                self,
 353                self.__callback_overload_warpper__(transform),
 354                max_workers,
 355                chunksize,
 356                executor,
 357            )
 358        )

 362    @overload

 364    @overload
 365    def find(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
 366    def find(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 367        """
 368        Returns the first element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 369
 370        Example 1:
 371        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 372        >>> it(lst).find(lambda x: x == 'b')
 373        'b'
 374        """
 375        return self.first_or_none(predicate)
 376
 377    def find_last(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]:
 378        """
 379        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 380
 381        Example 1:
 382        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 383        >>> it(lst).find_last(lambda x: x == 'b')
 384        'b'
 385        """
 386        return self.last_or_none(predicate)

 388    @overload
 389    def first(self) -> T: ...
 390    @overload
 391    def first(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> T: ...
 392    @overload
 393    def first(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T: ...
 394    @overload
 395    def first(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T: ...
 396    def first(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 397        """
 398        Returns first element.
 399
 400        Example 1:
 401        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 402        >>> it(lst).first()
 403        'a'
 404
 405        Example 2:
 406        >>> lst = []
 407        >>> it(lst).first()
 408        Traceback (most recent call last):
 409        ...
 410        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 411
 412        Example 3:
 413        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 414        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'b')
 415        'b'
 416
 417        Example 4:
 418        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 419        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'd')
 420        Traceback (most recent call last):
 421        ...
 422        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 423
 424        Example 5:
 425        >>> lst = [None]
 426        >>> it(lst).first() is None
 427        True
 428        """
 429        for e in self:
 430            if predicate is None or predicate(e):
 431                return e
 432        raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")
 433
 434    @overload
 435    def first_not_none_of(self: Sequence[Optional[U]]) -> U: ...
 436    @overload
 437    def first_not_none_of(
 438        self: Sequence[Optional[U]], transform: Callable[[Optional[U]], Optional[U]]

 440    @overload
 441    def first_not_none_of(
 442        self: Sequence[Optional[U]],
 443        transform: Callable[[Optional[U], int], Optional[U]],

 445    @overload
 446    def first_not_none_of(
 447        self: Sequence[Optional[U]],
 448        transform: Callable[[Optional[U], int, Sequence[Optional[U]]], Optional[U]],
 449    ) -> U: ...
 450    def first_not_none_of(
 451        self: Sequence[Optional[U]],
 452        transform: Optional[Callable[..., Optional[U]]] = None,
 453    ) -> U:
 454        """
 455        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 456
 457        Example 1:
 458        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 459        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 460        12
 461
 462        Example 2:
 463        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 464        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 465        Traceback (most recent call last):
 466        ...
 467        ValueError: No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.
 468        """
 469
 470        v = (
 471            self.first_not_none_of_or_none()
 472            if transform is None
 473            else self.first_not_none_of_or_none(transform)
 474        )
 475        if v is None:
 476            raise ValueError("No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.")
 477        return v
 478
 479    @overload
 480    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self) -> T: ...
 481    @overload
 482    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Callable[[T], T]) -> T: ...
 483    @overload
 484    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int], T]) -> T: ...
 485    @overload
 486    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], T]) -> T: ...
 487    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Optional[Callable[..., T]] = None) -> T:
 488        """
 489        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 490
 491        Example 1:
 492        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 493        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age'])
 494        12
 495
 496        Example 2:
 497        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 498        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age']) is None
 499        True
 500        """
 501        if transform is None:
 502            return self.first_or_none()
 503        return self.map_not_none(transform).first_or_none()

 505    @overload
 506    def first_or_none(self) -> T: ...
 507    @overload
 508    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
 509    @overload
 510    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
 511    @overload
 512    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
 513    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 514        """
 515        Returns the first element, or `None` if the Sequence is empty.
 516
 517        Example 1:
 518        >>> lst = []
 519        >>> it(lst).first_or_none() is None
 520        True
 521
 522        Example 2:
 523        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 524        >>> it(lst).first_or_none()
 525        'a'
 526
 527        Example 2:
 528        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 529        >>> it(lst).first_or_none(lambda x: x == 'b')
 530        'b'
 531        """
 532        if predicate is not None:
 533            return self.first_or_default(predicate, None)
 534        else:
 535            return self.first_or_default(None)
 536

 541    @overload

 545        self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool], default: U
 546    ) -> Union[T, U]: ...
 547    def first_or_default(  # type: ignore
 548        self, predicate: Union[Callable[..., bool], U], default: Optional[U] = None
 549    ) -> Union[T, U, None]:
 550        """
 551        Returns the first element, or the given [default] if the Sequence is empty.
 552
 553        Example 1:
 554        >>> lst = []
 555        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 556        'a'
 557
 558        Example 2:
 559        >>> lst = ['b']
 560        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 561        'b'
 562
 563        Example 3:
 564        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 565        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 566        'b'
 567
 568        Example 4:
 569        >>> lst = []
 570        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 571        'd'
 572        """
 573        seq = self
 574        if isinstance(predicate, Callable):
 575            seq = self.filter(predicate)  # type: ignore
 576        else:
 577            default = predicate
 578        return next(iter(seq), default)
 579

 581    def last(self) -> T: ...
 582    @overload
 583    def last(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> T: ...

 585    def last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T: ...
 586    @overload
 587    def last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T: ...
 588    def last(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 589        """
 590        Returns last element.
 591
 592        Example 1:
 593        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 594        >>> it(lst).last()
 595        'c'
 596
 597        Example 2:
 598        >>> lst = []
 599        >>> it(lst).last()
 600        Traceback (most recent call last):
 601        ...
 602        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 603        """
 604        v = self.last_or_none(predicate) if predicate is not None else self.last_or_none()
 605        if v is None:
 606            raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")
 607        return v

 615    @overload
 616    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
 617    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 618        """
 619        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 620
 621        Exmaple 1:
 622        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 623        >>> it(lst).last_or_none()
 624        'c'
 625
 626        Exmaple 2:
 627        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 628        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c')
 629        'b'
 630
 631        Exmaple 3:
 632        >>> lst = []
 633        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c') is None
 634        True
 635        """
 636        last: Optional[T] = None
 637        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 638            last = i
 639        return last

 641    def index_of_or_none(self, element: T) -> Optional[int]:
 642        """
 643        Returns first index of [element], or None if the collection does not contain element.
 644
 645        Example 1:
 646        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 647        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_none('b')
 648        1
 649
 650        Example 2:
 651        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 652        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_none('d')
 653        """
 654        for i, x in enumerate(self):
 655            if x == element:
 656                return i
 657        return None

 707    def last_index_of_or_none(self, element: T) -> Optional[int]:
 708        """
 709         Returns last index of [element], or None if the collection does not contain element.
 710
 711        Example 1:
 712        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
 713        >>> it(lst).last_index_of_or_none('b')
 714        3
 715
 716        Example 2:
 717        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 718        >>> it(lst).last_index_of_or_none('d')
 719        """
 720        seq = self.reversed()
 721        last_idx = len(seq) - 1
 722        for i, x in enumerate(seq):
 723            if x == element:
 724                return last_idx - i
 725        return None

1007    @overload
1008    def single(self) -> T: ...
1009    @overload
1010    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> T: ...
1011    @overload
1012    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T: ...
1013    @overload
1014    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T: ...
1015    def single(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
1016        """
1017        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or throws exception if there is no
1018        or more than one matching element.
1019
1020        Exmaple 1:
1021        >>> lst = ['a']
1022        >>> it(lst).single()
1023        'a'
1024
1025        Exmaple 2:
1026        >>> lst = []
1027        >>> it(lst).single() is None
1028        Traceback (most recent call last):
1029        ...
1030        ValueError: Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.
1031
1032        Exmaple 2:
1033        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
1034        >>> it(lst).single() is None
1035        Traceback (most recent call last):
1036        ...
1037        ValueError: Sequence contains more than one matching element.
1038        """
1039        single: Optional[T] = None
1040        found = False
1041        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
1042            if found:
1043                raise ValueError("Sequence contains more than one matching element.")
1044            single = i
1045            found = True
1046        if single is None:
1047            raise ValueError("Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.")
1048        return single
1049
1050    @overload
1051    def single_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]: ...
1052    @overload
1053    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1054    @overload
1055    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1056    @overload
1057    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1058    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
1059        """
1060        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if element was not found
1061        or more than one element was found.
1062
1063        Exmaple 1:
1064        >>> lst = ['a']
1065        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
1066        'a'
1067
1068        Exmaple 2:
1069        >>> lst = []
1070        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
1071
1072        Exmaple 2:
1073        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
1074        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
1075
1076        """
1077        single: Optional[T] = None
1078        found = False
1079        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
1080            if found:
1081                return None
1082            single = i
1083            found = True
1084        if not found:
1085            return None
1086        return single

1088    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
1089    def drop(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
1090        """
1091        Returns a Sequence containing all elements except first [n] elements.
1092
1093        Example 1:
1094        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1095        >>> it(lst).drop(0).to_list()
1096        ['a', 'b', 'c']
1097
1098        Example 2:
1099        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1100        >>> it(lst).drop(1).to_list()
1101        ['b', 'c']
1102
1103        Example 2:
1104        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1105        >>> it(lst).drop(4).to_list()
1106        []
1107        """
1108        if n < 0:
1109            raise ValueError(f"Requested element count {n} is less than zero.")
1110        if n == 0:
1111            return self
1112
1113        from .drop import DropTransform
1114
1115        return it(DropTransform(self, n))
1116

1120    @overload

1122    @overload
1123    def drop_while(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
1124    def drop_while(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
1125        """
1126        Returns a Sequence containing all elements except first elements that satisfy the given [predicate].
1127
1128        Example 1:
1129        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3, 4, 1]
1130        >>> it(lst).drop_while(lambda x: x < 3 ).to_list()
1131        [3, 4, 1]
1132        """
1133        from .drop_while import DropWhileTransform
1134
1135        return it(DropWhileTransform(self, self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)))

1162    @overload

1164    def skip_while(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
1165        """
1166        Returns a Sequence containing all elements except first elements that satisfy the given [predicate].
1167
1168        Example 1:
1169        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3, 4, 1]
1170        >>> it(lst).skip_while(lambda x: x < 3 ).to_list()

1172        """
1173        return self.drop_while(predicate)

1175    def take(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
1176        """
1177        Returns an Sequence containing first [n] elements.
1178
1179        Example 1:
1180        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1181        >>> it(a).take(0).to_list()
1182        []
1183
1184        Example 2:
1185        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1186        >>> it(a).take(2).to_list()
1187        ['a', 'b']
1188        """
1189        if n < 0:
1190            raise ValueError(f"Requested element count {n} is less than zero.")
1191        if n == 0:
1192            return Sequence([])
1193        from .take import TakeTransform
1194
1195        return it(TakeTransform(self, n))

1202    @overload

1205        """
1206        Returns an Sequence containing first elements satisfying the given [predicate].
1207

1217    def take_last(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
1218        """
1219        Returns an Sequence containing last [n] elements.
1220
1221        Example 1:
1222        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1223        >>> it(a).take_last(0).to_list()
1224        []
1225
1226        Example 2:
1227        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1228        >>> it(a).take_last(2).to_list()
1229        ['b', 'c']
1230        """
1231        if n < 0:
1232            raise ValueError(f"Requested element count {n} is less than zero.")
1233        if n == 0:
1234            return Sequence([])
1235
1236        return self.drop(len(self) - n)

1239    def sorted(self) -> Sequence[T]:
1240        """
1241        Returns an Sequence that yields elements of this Sequence sorted according to their natural sort order.
1242
1243        Example 1:
1244        >>> lst = ['b', 'a', 'e', 'c']

1249        >>> lst = [2, 1, 4, 3]

1251        [1, 2, 3, 4]
1252        """
1253        lst = list(self)
1254        lst.sort()  # type: ignore
1255        return it(lst)

1325        """

1327

1343    @overload

1345    def associate(self, transform: Callable[..., Tuple[K, V]]) -> Dict[K, V]:
1346        """
1347        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
1348        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
1349
1350        Example 1:
1351        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']
1352        >>> it(lst).associate(lambda x: (int(x), x))
1353        {1: '1', 2: '2', 3: '3'}
1354        """
1355        transform = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(transform)
1356        dic: Dict[K, V] = dict()
1357        for i in self:
1358            k, v = transform(i)
1359            dic[k] = v
1360        return dic

1373        self,
1374        key_selector: Callable[..., K],
1375        value_transform: Optional[Callable[[T], V]] = None,
1376    ) -> Union[Dict[K, T], Dict[K, V]]:
1377        """
1378        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
1379        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
1380
1381        Example 1:
1382        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']

1387        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']
1388        >>> it(lst).associate_by(lambda x: int(x), lambda x: x+x)
1389        {1: '11', 2: '22', 3: '33'}
1390
1391        """
1392        key_selector = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(key_selector)
1393
1394        dic: Dict[K, Any] = dict()
1395        for i in self:
1396            k = key_selector(i)
1397            dic[k] = i if value_transform is None else value_transform(i)
1398        return dic

1444        """
1445        Returns True if all elements of the Sequence satisfy the specified [predicate] function.
1446
1447        Example 1:
1448        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1449        >>> it(lst).all(lambda x: x > 0)
1450        True
1451        >>> it(lst).all(lambda x: x > 1)
1452        False
1453        """
1454        predicate = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)
1455        for i in self:
1456            if not predicate(i):
1457                return False
1458        return True

1494

1496        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]

1498        3

1504        if predicate is None:
1505            return len(self)
1506        predicate = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)
1507        return sum(1 for i in self if predicate(i))

1522    def element_at(self, index: int) -> T:
1523        """
1524        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence.

1527        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]

1534        Traceback (most recent call last):
1535        ...

1539            index, lambda index: throw(IndexError(f"Index {index} out of range"))

1556    @overload
1557    def element_at_or_else(self, index: int, default: T) -> T: ...
1558    @overload
1559    def element_at_or_else(self, index: int, default: Callable[[int], T]) -> T: ...
1560    def element_at_or_else(
1561        self, index: int, default: Union[Callable[[int], T], T, None] = None
1562    ) -> Optional[T]:
1563        """
1564        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence or the [default] value if the index is out of bounds.
1565
1566        Example 1:
1567        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1568        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_else(1, lambda x: 'default')
1569        2
1570        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_else(4, lambda x: 'default')
1571        'default'
1572
1573        """
1574        if index >= 0:
1575            if (
1576                isinstance(self.__transform__, NonTransform)
1577                and isinstance(self.__transform__.iter, list)
1578                and index < len(self.__transform__.iter)
1579            ):
1580                return self.__transform__.iter[index]
1581            for i, e in enumerate(self):
1582                if i == index:
1583                    return e
1584        return default(index) if callable(default) else default  # type: ignore
1585
1586    def element_at_or_default(self, index: int, default: T) -> T:
1587        """
1588        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence or the [default] value if the index is out of bounds.
1589
1590        Example 1:
1591        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1592        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_default(1, 'default')
1593        2
1594        >>> it(lst).element_at_or_default(4, 'default')
1595        'default'
1596
1597        """
1598        return self.element_at_or_else(index, default)
1599

1611        return self.element_at_or_else(index)

1651    @overload
1652    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[[T, T], T]) -> T: ...
1653    @overload
1654    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[[U, T], U], initial: U) -> U: ...
1655    def reduce(self, accumulator: Callable[..., U], initial: Optional[U] = None) -> Optional[U]:
1656        """
1657        Returns the result of applying the specified [accumulator] function to the given Sequence's elements.
1658
1659        Example 1:
1660        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1661        >>> it(lst).reduce(lambda x, y: x+y)
1662        6
1663        """
1664        result: Optional[U] = initial
1665        for i, e in enumerate(self):
1666            if i == 0 and initial is None:
1667                result = e  # type: ignore
1668                continue
1669
1670            result = accumulator(result, e)
1671        return result
1672
1673    def fold(self, initial: U, accumulator: Callable[[U, T], U]) -> U:

1678        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1679        >>> it(lst).fold(0, lambda x, y: x+y)
1680        6
1681        """
1682        return self.reduce(accumulator, initial)

1704        """

1714    @overload
1715    def max_by_or_none(self, selector: Callable[[T], int]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1716    @overload
1717    def max_by_or_none(self, selector: Callable[[T], float]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1718    def max_by_or_none(self, selector: Callable[[T], Union[float, int]]) -> Optional[T]:
1719        """
1720        Returns the first element yielding the largest value of the given function
1721        or `none` if there are no elements.
1722
1723        Example 1:
1724        >>> lst = [ { "name": "A", "num": 100 }, { "name": "B", "num": 200 }]
1725        >>> it(lst).max_by_or_none(lambda x: x["num"])
1726        {'name': 'B', 'num': 200}
1727
1728        Example 2:
1729        >>> lst = []
1730        >>> it(lst).max_by_or_none(lambda x: x["num"])
1731        """
1732
1733        max_item = None
1734        max_val = None
1735
1736        for item in self:
1737            val = selector(item)
1738            if max_val is None or val > max_val:
1739                max_item = item
1740                max_val = val
1741
1742        return max_item
1743

1748    def max_by(self, selector: Callable[[T], Union[float, int]]) -> T:

1750        Returns the first element yielding the largest value of the given function.
1751
1752        Example 1:
1753        >>> lst = [ { "name": "A", "num": 100 }, { "name": "B", "num": 200 }]
1754        >>> it(lst).max_by(lambda x: x["num"])
1755        {'name': 'B', 'num': 200}
1756
1757        Exmaple 2:
1758        >>> lst = []
1759        >>> it(lst).max_by(lambda x: x["num"])
1760        Traceback (most recent call last):
1761        ...
1762        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
1763        """
1764        max_item = self.max_by_or_none(selector)
1765        if max_item is None:
1766            raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")
1767        return max_item

1786    @overload
1787    def min_by_or_none(self, selector: Callable[[T], int]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1788    @overload
1789    def min_by_or_none(self, selector: Callable[[T], float]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1790    def min_by_or_none(self, selector: Callable[[T], float]) -> Optional[T]:
1791        """
1792        Returns the first element yielding the smallest value of the given function
1793        or `none` if there are no elements.
1794
1795        Example 1:
1796        >>> lst = [ { "name": "A", "num": 100 }, { "name": "B", "num": 200 }]
1797        >>> it(lst).min_by_or_none(lambda x: x["num"])
1798        {'name': 'A', 'num': 100}
1799
1800        Exmaple 2:
1801        >>> lst = []
1802        >>> it(lst).min_by_or_none(lambda x: x["num"])
1803        """
1804        min_item = None
1805        min_val = None
1806
1807        for item in self:
1808            val = selector(item)
1809            if min_val is None or val < min_val:
1810                min_item = item
1811                min_val = val
1812
1813        return min_item

2092        return self.map(transform).flatten()

2144        self, destination: Dict[K, List[T]], key_selector: Callable[..., K]

2148        and values being the corresponding elements of original collection.

2314        self,
2315        other: Iterable[Any],
2316        transform: Optional[Callable[..., V]] = None,  # type: ignore
2317    ) -> Sequence[Any]:
2318        """
2319        Returns a new Sequence of tuples, where each tuple contains two elements.
2320
2321        Example 1:
2322        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2323        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
2324        >>> it(lst1).zip(lst2).to_list()
2325        [('a', 1), ('b', 2), ('c', 3)]
2326
2327        Example 2:
2328        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2329        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
2330        >>> it(lst1).zip(lst2, lambda x, y: x + '__' +str( y)).to_list()
2331        ['a__1', 'b__2', 'c__3']
2332        """
2333        if transform is None:
2334
2335            def transform(*x: Any) -> Tuple[Any, ...]:
2336                return (*x,)
2337
2338        from .merging import MergingTransform
2339
2340        return it(MergingTransform(self, other, transform))

2375        self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Tuple[U, V]]
2376    ) -> "Tuple[ListLike[U], ListLike[V]]": ...
2377    def unzip(  # type: ignore
2378        self: Sequence[Tuple[U, V]],
2379        transform: Union[Optional[Callable[..., Tuple[Any, Any]]], bool] = None,
2380    ) -> "Tuple[ListLike[U], ListLike[V]]":
2381        """
2382        Returns a pair of lists, where first list is built from the first values of each pair from this array, second list is built from the second values of each pair from this array.
2383
2384        Example 1:
2385        >>> lst = [{'name': 'a', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'b', 'age': 12}, {'name': 'c', 'age': 13}]
2386        >>> a, b = it(lst).unzip(lambda x: (x['name'], x['age']))
2387        >>> a
2388        ['a', 'b', 'c']
2389        >>> b
2390        [11, 12, 13]
2391
2392        Example 1:
2393        >>> lst = [('a', 11), ('b', 12), ('c', 13)]
2394        >>> a, b = it(lst).unzip()
2395        >>> a
2396        ['a', 'b', 'c']
2397        >>> b
2398        [11, 12, 13]
2399        """
2400        from .list_like import ListLike
2401
2402        it = self
2403        if isinstance(transform, bool):
2404            transform = None
2405
2406        if transform is not None:
2407            transform = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(transform)
2408            it = it.map(transform)
2409
2410        a = it.map(lambda x: x[0])  # type: ignore
2411        b = it.map(lambda x: x[1])  # type: ignore
2412
2413        return ListLike(a), ListLike(b)
2414
2415    def with_index(self):
2416        """
2417        Returns a sequence containing the elements of this sequence and their indexes.
2418
2419        Example 1:
2420        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2421        >>> it(lst).with_index().to_list()
2422        [IndexedValue(0, a), IndexedValue(1, b), IndexedValue(2, c)]
2423        """
2424        return self.indexed()

2439        using the specified [random] instance as the source of randomness.

2452        Example 3:
2453        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']

2461    @overload
2462    def partition(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> "Tuple[ListLike[T], ListLike[T]]": ...
2463    @overload
2464    def partition(
2465        self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]
2466    ) -> "Tuple[ListLike[T], ListLike[T]]": ...
2467    @overload
2468    def partition(
2469        self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]
2470    ) -> "Tuple[ListLike[T], ListLike[T]]": ...
2471    def partition(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> "Tuple[ListLike[T], ListLike[T]]":
2472        """
2473        Partitions the elements of the given Sequence into two groups,
2474        the first group containing the elements for which the predicate returns true,
2475        and the second containing the rest.
2476
2477        Example 1:
2478        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', '2']
2479        >>> it(lst).partition(lambda x: x.isalpha())
2480        (['a', 'b', 'c'], ['2'])
2481
2482        Example 2:
2483        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', '2']
2484        >>> it(lst).partition(lambda _, i: i % 2 == 0)
2485        (['a', 'c'], ['b', '2'])
2486        """
2487        from .list_like import ListLike
2488
2489        predicate_a = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)
2490        predicate_b = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)
2491        part_a = self.filter(predicate_a)
2492        part_b = self.filter(lambda x: not predicate_b(x))
2493        return ListLike(part_a), ListLike(part_b)

2530    def windowed(self, size: int, step: int = 1, partialWindows: bool = False) -> Sequence[List[T]]:
2531        """
2532         Returns a Sequence of all possible sliding windows of size [size] from the given Sequence.
2533
2534        Example 1:
2535        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']

2548        """
2549        from .windowed import WindowedTransform

2583    def concat(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2584        """
2585        Returns a Sequence of all elements of the given Sequence, followed by all elements of the given Sequence.
2586
2587        Example 1:
2588        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2589        >>> lst2 = [1, 2, 3]

2596        >>> lst3 = [4, 5, 6]
2597        >>> it(lst1).concat(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2598        ['a', 'b', 'c', 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
2599        """
2600        from .concat import ConcatTransform
2601
2602        return it(ConcatTransform([self, *other]))

2604    def intersect(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2605        """
2606        Returns a set containing all elements that are contained by both this collection and the specified collection.
2607
2608        The returned set preserves the element iteration order of the original collection.
2609
2610        To get a set containing all elements that are contained at least in one of these collections use union.
2611
2612        Example 1:
2613        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2614        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'c']
2615        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2).to_list()
2616        ['c']
2617
2618        Example 2:
2619        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2620        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b', 'c']
2621        >>> lst3 = ['a3', 'b', 'c3']
2622        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2623        ['b']
2624
2625
2626        Example 1:
2627        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'a', 'c']
2628        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'a']
2629        >>> it(lst1).intersect(lst2).to_list()
2630        ['a']
2631        """
2632        from .intersection import IntersectionTransform
2633
2634        return it(IntersectionTransform([self, *other]))
2635
2636    def union(self, *other: Sequence[T]) -> Sequence[T]:
2637        """
2638        Returns a set containing all distinct elements from both collections.
2639
2640        The returned set preserves the element iteration order of the original collection. Those elements of the other collection that are unique are iterated in the end in the order of the other collection.
2641
2642        To get a set containing all elements that are contained in both collections use intersect.
2643
2644        Example 1:
2645        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2646        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'c']
2647        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2).to_list()
2648        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'a2', 'b2']
2649
2650        Example 2:
2651        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'b', 'c']
2652        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b', 'c']
2653        >>> lst3 = ['a3', 'b', 'c3']
2654        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2, lst3).to_list()
2655        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'a2', 'a3', 'c3']
2656
2657
2658        Example 1:
2659        >>> lst1 = ['a', 'a', 'c']
2660        >>> lst2 = ['a2', 'b2', 'a']
2661        >>> it(lst1).union(lst2).to_list()
2662        ['a', 'c', 'a2', 'b2']
2663        """
2664        return self.concat(*other).distinct()
2665

2677    @overload
2678    def progress(self) -> Sequence[T]: ...
2679    @overload

2681        self, progress_func: Union[Literal["tqdm"], Literal["tqdm_rich"]]
2682    ) -> Sequence[T]: ...
2683    @overload
2684    def progress(self, progress_func: Callable[[Iterable[T]], Iterable[T]]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
2685    def progress(
2686        self,
2687        progress_func: Union[
2688            Callable[[Iterable[T]], Iterable[T]],
2689            Literal["tqdm"],
2690            Literal["tqdm_rich"],
2691            None,
2692        ] = None,
2693    ) -> Sequence[T]:
2694        """
2695        Returns a Sequence that enable a progress bar for the given Sequence.
2696
2697        Example 1:
2698        >>> from tqdm import tqdm
2699        >>> from time import sleep
2700        >>> it(range(10)).progress(lambda x: tqdm(x, total=len(x))).parallel_map(lambda x: sleep(0.), max_workers=5).to_list() and None
2701        >>> for _ in it(list(range(10))).progress(lambda x: tqdm(x, total=len(x))).to_list(): pass
2702        """
2703        if progress_func is not None and callable(progress_func):
2704            from .progress import ProgressTransform
2705
2706            return it(ProgressTransform(self, progress_func))
2707
2708        def import_tqdm():
2709            if progress_func == "tqdm_rich":
2710                from tqdm.rich import tqdm
2711            else:
2712                from tqdm import tqdm
2713            return tqdm
2714
2715        try:
2716            tqdm = import_tqdm()
2717        except ImportError:
2718            from pip import main as pip
2719
2720            pip(["install", "tqdm"])
2721            tqdm = import_tqdm()
2722
2723        return it(tqdm(self, total=len(self)))

2725    def typing_as(self, typ: Type[U]) -> Sequence[U]:
2726        """
2727        Cast the element as specific Type to gain code completion base on type annotations.
2728        """
2729        el = self.first_not_none_of_or_none()
2730        if el is None or isinstance(el, typ) or not isinstance(el, dict):
2731            return self  # type: ignore
2732
2733        class AttrDict(Dict[str, Any]):
2734            def __init__(self, value: Dict[str, Any]) -> None:
2735                super().__init__(**value)
2736                setattr(self, "__dict__", value)
2737                self.__getattr__ = value.__getitem__
2738                self.__setattr__ = value.__setattr__  # type: ignore
2739
2740        return self.map(AttrDict)  # type: ignore  # use https://github.com/cdgriffith/Box ?

2799    def let(self, block: Callable[[Sequence[T]], U]) -> U:
2800        """
2801        Calls the specified function [block] with `self` value as its argument and returns its result.

2804        >>> it(['a', 'b', 'c']).let(lambda x: x.map(lambda y: y + '!')).to_list()

2809    def also(self, block: Callable[[Sequence[T]], Any]) -> Sequence[T]:
2810        """
2811        Calls the specified function [block] with `self` value as its argument and returns `self` value.

2814        >>> it(['a', 'b', 'c']).also(lambda x: x.map(lambda y: y + '!')).to_list()
2815        ['a', 'b', 'c']

2817        block(self)

2837        False

2862    def __getitem__(self, key: int):
2863        """
2864        Returns the element at the specified [index] in the Sequence.
2865
2866        Example 1:
2867        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
2868        >>> it(lst)[1]
2869        2
2870
2871        Example 2:
2872        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
2873        >>> it(lst)[3]
2874        Traceback (most recent call last):
2875        ...
2876        IndexError: Index 3 out of range
2877        """

2880    @overload
2881    def __callback_overload_warpper__(self, callback: Callable[[T], U]) -> Callable[[T], U]: ...
2882    @overload
2883    def __callback_overload_warpper__(
2884        self, callback: Callable[[T, int], U]
2885    ) -> Callable[[T], U]: ...
2886    @overload
2887    def __callback_overload_warpper__(
2888        self, callback: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], U]
2889    ) -> Callable[[T], U]: ...
2890    def __callback_overload_warpper__(self, callback: Callable[..., U]) -> Callable[[T], U]:
2891        if hasattr(callback, "__code__"):
2892            if callback.__code__.co_argcount == 2:
2893                index = AutoIncrementIndex()
2894                return lambda x: callback(x, index())
2895            if callback.__code__.co_argcount == 3:
2896                index = AutoIncrementIndex()
2897                return lambda x: callback(x, index(), self)
2898        return callback
2899
2900
2901class AutoIncrementIndex:
2902    idx = 0
2903
2904    def __call__(self) -> int:
2905        val = self.idx
2906        self.idx += 1
2907        return val
2908

2910class IndexedValue(NamedTuple, Generic[T]):
2911    val: T
2912    idx: int
2913
2914    def __repr__(self) -> str:
2915        return f"IndexedValue({self.idx}, {self.val})"

2923    return value if value is not None else default

2930class SequenceProducer:
2931    @overload
2932    def __call__(self, elements: List[T]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
2933    @overload
2934    def __call__(self, elements: Iterable[T]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
2935    @overload
2936    def __call__(self, *elements: T) -> Sequence[T]: ...
2937    def __call__(self, *iterable: Union[Iterable[T], List[T], T]) -> Sequence[T]:  # type: ignore
2938        if len(iterable) == 1:
2939            iter = iterable[0]
2940            if isinstance(iter, Sequence):
2941                return iter  # type: ignore
2942            if isinstance(iter, Iterable) and not isinstance(iter, str):
2943                return Sequence(iter)  # type: ignore
2944        return Sequence(iterable)  # type: ignore
2945
2946    def json(self, filepath: str, **kwargs: Dict[str, Any]) -> Sequence[Any]:
2947        """
2948        Reads and parses the input of a json file.
2949        """
2950        import json
2951
2952        with open(filepath, "r") as f:
2953            data = json.load(f, **kwargs)  # type: ignore
2954            return self(data)
2955
2956    def csv(self, filepath: str):
2957        """
2958        Reads and parses the input of a csv file.
2959        """
2960        return self.read_csv(filepath)
2961
2962    def read_csv(self, filepath: str, header: Optional[int] = 0):
2963        """
2964        Reads and parses the input of a csv file.
2965
2966        Example 1:
2967        >>> it.read_csv('tests/data/a.csv').to_list()
2968        [{'a': 'a1', 'b': '1'}, {'a': 'a2', 'b': '2'}]
2969        """
2970        import csv
2971
2972        it = self
2973        with open(filepath) as f:
2974            reader = csv.reader(f)
2975            iter = it(*reader)
2976            if header is None or header < 0:
2977                return iter
2978
2979            headers = iter.element_at_or_none(header)
2980            if headers is not None:
2981                if header == 0:
2982                    iter = iter.skip(1)
2983                else:
2984                    iter = iter.filter(lambda _, i: i != header)
2985
2986                return iter.map(
2987                    lambda row: it(row).associate_by(
2988                        lambda _, ordinal: headers[ordinal]
2989                        if ordinal < len(headers)
2990                        else f"undefined_{ordinal}"
2991                    )
2992                )
2993            return iter
2994
2995    def __repr__(self) -> str:
2996        return __package__ or self.__class__.__name__
2997

3000"""

3003    Example 1:
3004>>> sequence('hello', 'world').map(lambda x: x.upper()).to_list()

3006
3007    Example 2:

3011    Example 3:
3012>>> sequence(range(10)).map(lambda x: x*x).to_list()

3016seq = sequence
3017"""
3018    Creates an iterator from a list of elements or given Iterable.
3019
3020    Example 1:
3021>>> seq('hello', 'world').map(lambda x: x.upper()).to_list()
3022['HELLO', 'WORLD']
3023
3024    Example 2:
3025>>> seq(['hello', 'world']).map(lambda x: x.upper()).to_list()
3026['HELLO', 'WORLD']
3027
3028    Example 3:
3029>>> seq(range(10)).map(lambda x: x*x).to_list()
3030[0, 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81]
3031"""
3032
3033it = sequence
3034"""
3035    Creates an iterator from a list of elements or given Iterable.
3036
3037    Example 1:
3038>>> it('hello', 'world').map(lambda x: x.upper()).to_list()
3039['HELLO', 'WORLD']
3040
3041    Example 2:
3042>>> it(['hello', 'world']).map(lambda x: x.upper()).to_list()
3043['HELLO', 'WORLD']
3044
3045    Example 3:
3046>>> it(range(10)).map(lambda x: x*x).to_list()
3047[0, 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81]
3048"""
3049

3051if __name__ == "__main__":
3052    import doctest

3054    doctest.testmod()
class Sequence(typing.Generic[~T], typing.Iterable[~T]): 
  53class Sequence(Generic[T], Iterable[T]):
  54    """
  55    Given an [iterator] function constructs a [Sequence] that returns values through the [Iterator]
  56    provided by that function.
  57
  58    The values are evaluated lazily, and the sequence is potentially infinite.
  59    """
  60
  61    __transform__: Transform[Any, T]
  62
  63    def __init__(self, iterable: Union[Iterable[T], Transform[Any, T]]) -> None:
  64        super().__init__()
  65
  66        self.__transform__ = new_transform(iterable)
  67
  68    @cached_property
  69    def transforms(self):
  70        return [*self.__transform__.transforms()]
  71
  72    @property
  73    def data(self) -> List[T]:
  74        if self.__transform__.cache is None:
  75            from .error import LazyEvaluationException
  76
  77            raise LazyEvaluationException("The sequence has not been evaluated yet.")
  78        return self.__transform__.cache
  79
  80    def dedup(self) -> Sequence[T]:
  81        """
  82        Removes consecutive repeated elements in the sequence.
  83
  84        If the sequence is sorted, this removes all duplicates.
  85
  86        Example 1:
  87        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
  88        >>> it(lst).dedup().to_list()
  89        ['a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
  90
  91        Example 1:
  92        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
  93        >>> it(lst).sorted().dedup().to_list()
  94        ['a1', 'a2', 'b2']
  95        """
  96        return self.dedup_by(lambda x: x)
  97
  98    @overload
  99    def dedup_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T], Any]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 100    @overload
 101    def dedup_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T, int], Any]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 102    @overload
 103    def dedup_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Any]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 104    def dedup_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., Any]) -> Sequence[T]:
 105        """
 106        Removes all but the first of consecutive elements in the sequence that resolve to the same key.
 107        """
 108        return self.dedup_into_group_by(key_selector).map(lambda x: x[0])
 109
 110    @overload
 111    def dedup_with_count_by(self, key_selector: Callable[[T], Any]) -> Sequence[Tuple[T, int]]: ...
 112    @overload
 113    def dedup_with_count_by(
 114        self, key_selector: Callable[[T, int], Any]
 115    ) -> Sequence[Tuple[T, int]]: ...
 116    @overload
 117    def dedup_with_count_by(
 118        self, key_selector: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Any]
 119    ) -> Sequence[Tuple[T, int]]: ...
 120    def dedup_with_count_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., Any]) -> Sequence[Tuple[T, int]]:
 121        """
 122        Removes all but the first of consecutive elements and its count that resolve to the same key.
 123
 124        Example 1:
 125        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
 126        >>> it(lst).dedup_with_count_by(lambda x: x).to_list()
 127        [('a1', 2), ('b2', 1), ('a2', 1), ('a1', 1)]
 128
 129        Example 1:
 130        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a1', 'b2', 'a2', 'a1']
 131        >>> it(lst).sorted().dedup_with_count_by(lambda x: x).to_list()
 132        [('a1', 3), ('a2', 1), ('b2', 1)]
 133        """
 134        return self.dedup_into_group_by(key_selector).map(lambda x: (x[0], len(x)))

 138    @overload

 144    def dedup_into_group_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., Any]) -> Sequence[List[T]]:
 145        from .dedup import DedupTransform

 147        return it(DedupTransform(self, key_selector))

 149    @overload

 151    @overload

 153    @overload

 155    def filter(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
 156        """
 157        Returns a Sequence containing only elements matching the given [predicate].
 158
 159        Example 1:
 160        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
 161        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
 162        ['a1', 'a2']
 163
 164        Example 2:
 165        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
 166        >>> it(lst).filter(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') or i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
 167        ['a1', 'b2', 'a2']
 168        """
 169        from .filtering import FilteringTransform
 170
 171        return it(FilteringTransform(self, self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)))

 173    def filter_is_instance(self, typ: Type[U]) -> Sequence[U]:
 174        """
 175        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are instances of specified type parameter typ.
 176
 177        Example 1:
 178        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 1, 'b2', 3]
 179        >>> it(lst).filter_is_instance(int).to_list()
 180        [1, 3]
 181
 182        """
 183        return self.filter(lambda x: isinstance(x, typ))  # type: ignore

 187    @overload

 189    @overload
 190    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Sequence[T]: ...
 191    def filter_not(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> Sequence[T]:
 192        """
 193        Returns a Sequence containing all elements not matching the given [predicate].
 194
 195        Example 1:
 196        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'b1', 'b2', 'a2']
 197        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x: x.startswith('a')).to_list()
 198        ['b1', 'b2']
 199
 200        Example 2:
 201        >>> lst = [ 'a1', 'a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 202        >>> it(lst).filter_not(lambda x, i: x.startswith('a') and i % 2 == 0 ).to_list()
 203        ['a2', 'b1', 'b2']
 204        """
 205        predicate = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)
 206        return self.filter(lambda x: not predicate(x))

 212    def filter_not_none(self: Sequence[Optional[U]]) -> Sequence[U]:
 213        """
 214        Returns a Sequence containing all elements that are not `None`.
 215

 217        >>> lst = [ 'a', None, 'b']

 220        """
 221        return self.filter(lambda x: x is not None)  # type: ignore

 223    @overload
 224    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T], U]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 225    @overload

 227    @overload
 228    def map(self, transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], U]) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 229    def map(self, transform: Callable[..., U]) -> Sequence[U]:
 230        """
 231        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 232        to each element in the original Sequence.
 233
 234        Example 1:
 235        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 236        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
 237        [12, 13]
 238
 239        Example 2:
 240        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 241        >>> it(lst).map(lambda x, i: x['name'] + str(i)).to_list()
 242        ['A0', 'B1']
 243
 244        Example 3:
 245        >>> lst = ['hi', 'abc']
 246        >>> it(lst).map(len).to_list()
 247        [2, 3]
 248        """
 249        from .mapping import MappingTransform
 250
 251        return it(MappingTransform(self, self.__callback_overload_warpper__(transform)))

 261    @overload
 262    async def map_async(
 263        self,
 264        transform: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], Awaitable[U]],
 265        return_exceptions: Literal[False] = False,
 266    ) -> Sequence[U]: ...
 267    async def map_async(
 268        self, transform: Callable[..., Awaitable[U]], return_exceptions: bool = False
 269    ):
 270        """
 271        Similar to `.map()` but you can input a async transform then await it.
 272        """
 273        from asyncio import gather
 274
 275        if return_exceptions:
 276            return it(await gather(*self.map(transform), return_exceptions=True))
 277        return it(await gather(*self.map(transform)))

 294        >>> it(lst).map_not_none(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()

 324        self,
 325        transform: Callable[..., U],
 326        max_workers: Optional[int] = None,
 327        chunksize: int = 1,
 328        executor: ParallelMappingTransform.Executor = "Thread",
 329    ) -> Sequence[U]:
 330        """
 331        Returns a Sequence containing the results of applying the given [transform] function
 332        to each element in the original Sequence.
 333
 334        Example 1:
 335        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 336        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()

 341        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x: x['age'], max_workers=2).to_list()
 342        [12, 13]

 344        Example 3:
 345        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 13}]
 346        >>> it(lst).parallel_map(lambda x, i: x['age'] + i, max_workers=2).to_list()
 347        [12, 14]
 348        """
 349        from .parallel_mapping import ParallelMappingTransform
 350
 351        return it(
 352            ParallelMappingTransform(

 354                self.__callback_overload_warpper__(transform),
 355                max_workers,
 356                chunksize,

 395    @overload
 396    def first(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T: ...
 397    def first(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 398        """
 399        Returns first element.
 400
 401        Example 1:
 402        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 403        >>> it(lst).first()
 404        'a'
 405
 406        Example 2:
 407        >>> lst = []
 408        >>> it(lst).first()
 409        Traceback (most recent call last):
 410        ...
 411        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 412
 413        Example 3:
 414        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 415        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'b')
 416        'b'
 417
 418        Example 4:
 419        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 420        >>> it(lst).first(lambda x: x == 'd')
 421        Traceback (most recent call last):
 422        ...
 423        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 424
 425        Example 5:
 426        >>> lst = [None]
 427        >>> it(lst).first() is None
 428        True
 429        """
 430        for e in self:
 431            if predicate is None or predicate(e):
 432                return e
 433        raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")

 449        transform: Callable[[Optional[U], int, Sequence[Optional[U]]], Optional[U]],
 450    ) -> U: ...
 451    def first_not_none_of(
 452        self: Sequence[Optional[U]],
 453        transform: Optional[Callable[..., Optional[U]]] = None,
 454    ) -> U:
 455        """
 456        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 457
 458        Example 1:
 459        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 460        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 461        12
 462
 463        Example 2:
 464        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 465        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of(lambda x: x['age'])
 466        Traceback (most recent call last):
 467        ...
 468        ValueError: No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.
 469        """
 470
 471        v = (
 472            self.first_not_none_of_or_none()
 473            if transform is None
 474            else self.first_not_none_of_or_none(transform)
 475        )
 476        if v is None:
 477            raise ValueError("No element of the Sequence was transformed to a non-none value.")
 478        return v

 486    @overload

 488    def first_not_none_of_or_none(self, transform: Optional[Callable[..., T]] = None) -> T:
 489        """
 490        Returns the first non-`None` result of applying the given [transform] function to each element in the original collection.
 491
 492        Example 1:
 493        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': 12}]
 494        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age'])
 495        12
 496
 497        Example 2:
 498        >>> lst = [{ 'name': 'A', 'age': None}, { 'name': 'B', 'age': None}]
 499        >>> it(lst).first_not_none_of_or_none(lambda x: x['age']) is None
 500        True
 501        """
 502        if transform is None:
 503            return self.first_or_none()
 504        return self.map_not_none(transform).first_or_none()

 510    @overload

 512    @overload

 514    def first_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 515        """
 516        Returns the first element, or `None` if the Sequence is empty.
 517
 518        Example 1:
 519        >>> lst = []
 520        >>> it(lst).first_or_none() is None
 521        True
 522
 523        Example 2:
 524        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 525        >>> it(lst).first_or_none()
 526        'a'
 527
 528        Example 2:
 529        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 530        >>> it(lst).first_or_none(lambda x: x == 'b')
 531        'b'
 532        """
 533        if predicate is not None:
 534            return self.first_or_default(predicate, None)
 535        else:
 536            return self.first_or_default(None)

 538    @overload
 539    def first_or_default(self, default: U) -> Union[T, U]: ...
 540    @overload
 541    def first_or_default(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool], default: U) -> Union[T, U]: ...
 542    @overload

 544    @overload
 545    def first_or_default(
 546        self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool], default: U
 547    ) -> Union[T, U]: ...
 548    def first_or_default(  # type: ignore
 549        self, predicate: Union[Callable[..., bool], U], default: Optional[U] = None
 550    ) -> Union[T, U, None]:
 551        """
 552        Returns the first element, or the given [default] if the Sequence is empty.
 553
 554        Example 1:
 555        >>> lst = []
 556        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 557        'a'
 558
 559        Example 2:
 560        >>> lst = ['b']
 561        >>> it(lst).first_or_default('a')
 562        'b'
 563
 564        Example 3:
 565        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 566        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 567        'b'
 568
 569        Example 4:
 570        >>> lst = []
 571        >>> it(lst).first_or_default(lambda x: x == 'b', 'd')
 572        'd'
 573        """
 574        seq = self
 575        if isinstance(predicate, Callable):
 576            seq = self.filter(predicate)  # type: ignore
 577        else:
 578            default = predicate
 579        return next(iter(seq), default)

 585    @overload

 587    @overload
 588    def last(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T: ...
 589    def last(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
 590        """
 591        Returns last element.
 592
 593        Example 1:
 594        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 595        >>> it(lst).last()
 596        'c'
 597
 598        Example 2:
 599        >>> lst = []
 600        >>> it(lst).last()
 601        Traceback (most recent call last):
 602        ...
 603        ValueError: Sequence is empty.
 604        """
 605        v = self.last_or_none(predicate) if predicate is not None else self.last_or_none()
 606        if v is None:
 607            raise ValueError("Sequence is empty.")
 608        return v

 610    @overload
 611    def last_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]: ...
 612    @overload
 613    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
 614    @overload
 615    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
 616    @overload
 617    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
 618    def last_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
 619        """
 620        Returns the last element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if no such element was found.
 621
 622        Exmaple 1:
 623        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 624        >>> it(lst).last_or_none()
 625        'c'
 626
 627        Exmaple 2:
 628        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 629        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c')
 630        'b'
 631
 632        Exmaple 3:
 633        >>> lst = []
 634        >>> it(lst).last_or_none(lambda x: x != 'c') is None
 635        True
 636        """
 637        last: Optional[T] = None
 638        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
 639            last = i
 640        return last

 642    def index_of_or_none(self, element: T) -> Optional[int]:
 643        """
 644        Returns first index of [element], or None if the collection does not contain element.
 645
 646        Example 1:
 647        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 648        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_none('b')
 649        1
 650
 651        Example 2:
 652        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 653        >>> it(lst).index_of_or_none('d')
 654        """
 655        for i, x in enumerate(self):
 656            if x == element:
 657                return i
 658        return None
 659

 661        """
 662        Returns first index of [element], or -1 if the collection does not contain element.

 667        1
 668
 669        Example 2:
 670        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']

 672        -1
 673        """
 674        return none_or(self.index_of_or_none(element), -1)

 708    def last_index_of_or_none(self, element: T) -> Optional[int]:
 709        """
 710         Returns last index of [element], or None if the collection does not contain element.
 711
 712        Example 1:
 713        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
 714        >>> it(lst).last_index_of_or_none('b')
 715        3
 716
 717        Example 2:
 718        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
 719        >>> it(lst).last_index_of_or_none('d')
 720        """
 721        seq = self.reversed()
 722        last_idx = len(seq) - 1
 723        for i, x in enumerate(seq):
 724            if x == element:
 725                return last_idx - i
 726        return None

1008    @overload
1009    def single(self) -> T: ...
1010    @overload
1011    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> T: ...
1012    @overload
1013    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> T: ...
1014    @overload
1015    def single(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> T: ...
1016    def single(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> T:
1017        """
1018        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or throws exception if there is no
1019        or more than one matching element.
1020
1021        Exmaple 1:
1022        >>> lst = ['a']
1023        >>> it(lst).single()
1024        'a'
1025
1026        Exmaple 2:
1027        >>> lst = []
1028        >>> it(lst).single() is None
1029        Traceback (most recent call last):
1030        ...
1031        ValueError: Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.
1032
1033        Exmaple 2:
1034        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
1035        >>> it(lst).single() is None
1036        Traceback (most recent call last):
1037        ...
1038        ValueError: Sequence contains more than one matching element.
1039        """
1040        single: Optional[T] = None
1041        found = False
1042        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
1043            if found:
1044                raise ValueError("Sequence contains more than one matching element.")
1045            single = i
1046            found = True
1047        if single is None:
1048            raise ValueError("Sequence contains no element matching the predicate.")
1049        return single
1050
1051    @overload
1052    def single_or_none(self) -> Optional[T]: ...
1053    @overload
1054    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1055    @overload
1056    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1057    @overload
1058    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Callable[[T, int, Sequence[T]], bool]) -> Optional[T]: ...
1059    def single_or_none(self, predicate: Optional[Callable[..., bool]] = None) -> Optional[T]:
1060        """
1061        Returns the single element matching the given [predicate], or `None` if element was not found
1062        or more than one element was found.
1063
1064        Exmaple 1:
1065        >>> lst = ['a']
1066        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
1067        'a'
1068
1069        Exmaple 2:
1070        >>> lst = []
1071        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
1072
1073        Exmaple 2:
1074        >>> lst = ['a', 'b']
1075        >>> it(lst).single_or_none()
1076
1077        """
1078        single: Optional[T] = None
1079        found = False
1080        for i in self if predicate is None else self.filter(predicate):
1081            if found:
1082                return None
1083            single = i
1084            found = True
1085        if not found:
1086            return None
1087        return single

1089    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
1090    def drop(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
1091        """
1092        Returns a Sequence containing all elements except first [n] elements.
1093
1094        Example 1:
1095        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1096        >>> it(lst).drop(0).to_list()
1097        ['a', 'b', 'c']
1098
1099        Example 2:
1100        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1101        >>> it(lst).drop(1).to_list()
1102        ['b', 'c']
1103
1104        Example 2:
1105        >>> lst = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1106        >>> it(lst).drop(4).to_list()
1107        []
1108        """
1109        if n < 0:
1110            raise ValueError(f"Requested element count {n} is less than zero.")
1111        if n == 0:
1112            return self
1113
1114        from .drop import DropTransform
1115
1116        return it(DropTransform(self, n))
1117

1177        """

1218    def take_last(self, n: int) -> Sequence[T]:
1219        """
1220        Returns an Sequence containing last [n] elements.
1221
1222        Example 1:
1223        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1224        >>> it(a).take_last(0).to_list()
1225        []
1226
1227        Example 2:
1228        >>> a = ['a', 'b', 'c']
1229        >>> it(a).take_last(2).to_list()
1230        ['b', 'c']

1232        if n < 0:
1233            raise ValueError(f"Requested element count {n} is less than zero.")

1235            return Sequence([])

1239    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
1240    def sorted(self) -> Sequence[T]:
1241        """
1242        Returns an Sequence that yields elements of this Sequence sorted according to their natural sort order.
1243
1244        Example 1:
1245        >>> lst = ['b', 'a', 'e', 'c']
1246        >>> it(lst).sorted().to_list()
1247        ['a', 'b', 'c', 'e']
1248
1249         Example 2:
1250        >>> lst = [2, 1, 4, 3]
1251        >>> it(lst).sorted().to_list()
1252        [1, 2, 3, 4]
1253        """
1254        lst = list(self)
1255        lst.sort()  # type: ignore
1256        return it(lst)

1269    def sorted_by(self, key_selector: Callable[..., SupportsRichComparisonT]) -> Sequence[T]:
1270        """
1271        Returns a sequence that yields elements of this sequence sorted according to natural sort
1272        order of the value returned by specified [key_selector] function.
1273
1274        Example 1:
1275        >>> lst = [ {'name': 'A', 'age': 12 }, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10 }, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11 } ]
1276        >>> it(lst).sorted_by(lambda x: x['name']).to_list()
1277        [{'name': 'A', 'age': 12}, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10}]
1278        >>> it(lst).sorted_by(lambda x: x['age']).to_list()
1279        [{'name': 'C', 'age': 10}, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11}, {'name': 'A', 'age': 12}]
1280        """
1281        lst = list(self)
1282        lst.sort(key=self.__callback_overload_warpper__(key_selector))
1283        return it(lst)

1285    def sorted_descending(self) -> Sequence[T]:
1286        """
1287        Returns a Sequence of all elements sorted descending according to their natural sort order.
1288
1289        Example 1:
1290        >>> lst = ['b', 'c', 'a']
1291        >>> it(lst).sorted_descending().to_list()
1292        ['c', 'b', 'a']
1293        """
1294        return self.sorted().reversed()

1311        """
1312        Returns a sequence that yields elements of this sequence sorted descending according
1313        to natural sort order of the value returned by specified [key_selector] function.
1314
1315        Example 1:
1316        >>> lst = [ {'name': 'A', 'age': 12 }, {'name': 'C', 'age': 10 }, {'name': 'B', 'age': 11 } ]

1324    # noinspection PyShadowingNames
1325    def sorted_with(self, comparator: Callable[[T, T], int]) -> Sequence[T]:
1326        """
1327        Returns a sequence that yields elements of this sequence sorted according to the specified [comparator].
1328
1329        Example 1:
1330        >>> lst = ['aa', 'bbb', 'c']
1331        >>> it(lst).sorted_with(lambda a, b: len(a)-len(b)).to_list()
1332        ['c', 'aa', 'bbb']

1334        from functools import cmp_to_key
1335
1336        lst = list(self)
1337        lst.sort(key=cmp_to_key(comparator))

1344    @overload

1346    def associate(self, transform: Callable[..., Tuple[K, V]]) -> Dict[K, V]:
1347        """
1348        Returns a [Dict] containing key-value Tuple provided by [transform] function
1349        applied to elements of the given Sequence.
1350
1351        Example 1:
1352        >>> lst = ['1', '2', '3']
1353        >>> it(lst).associate(lambda x: (int(x), x))
1354        {1: '1', 2: '2', 3: '3'}
1355        """
1356        transform = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(transform)
1357        dic: Dict[K, V] = dict()
1358        for i in self:
1359            k, v = transform(i)
1360            dic[k] = v
1361        return dic

1442    @overload

1444    def all(self, predicate: Callable[..., bool]) -> bool:
1445        """
1446        Returns True if all elements of the Sequence satisfy the specified [predicate] function.
1447
1448        Example 1:
1449        >>> lst = [1, 2, 3]
1450        >>> it(lst).all(lambda x: x > 0)
1451        True
1452        >>> it(lst).all(lambda x: x > 1)
1453        False
1454        """
1455        predicate = self.__callback_overload_warpper__(predicate)
1456        for i in self:
1457            if not predicate(i):
1458                return False
1459        return True
